==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mute
<hw>Mute</hw> <pr>(m⟦umac⟧t)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>mutare</ets> to change. See <er>Molt</er>.]</ety> <def>To cast off;
to molt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Have I <qex>muted</qex> all my feathers?</q> <rj><qau>Beau. &
Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mute
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>mutir</ets>,
<ets>⟦eacute⟧meutir</ets>, OF. <ets>esmeltir</ets>, fr. OD.
<ets>smelten</ets>, prop., to melt. See <er>Smelt</er>.]</ety> <def>To
eject the contents of the bowels; -- said of birds.</def> <rj><au>B.
Jonson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mute
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>The dung of birds.</def>
<rj><au>Hudibras.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mute
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>mutus</ets>; cf. Gr.
<grk>my`ein</grk> to shut, Skr. <ets>m⟦umac⟧ta</ets> bound,
<ets>m⟦umac⟧ka</ets> dumb: cf. OE. <ets>muet</ets>, fr. F.
<ets>muet</ets>, a dim. of OF. <ets>mu</ets>, L.
<ets>mutus</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Not speaking; uttering no
sound; silent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the heavenly choir stood <qex>mute</qex>,⟦br⟧
And silence was in heaven.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In law a prisoner is said to stand <xex>mute</xex>,
when, upon being arranged, he makes no answer, or does not plead
directly, or will not put himself on trial.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Incapable of speaking; dumb.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not uttered; unpronounced; silent; also, produced by
complete closure of the mouth organs which interrupt the passage of
breath; -- said of certain letters. See 5th <er>Mute</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not giving a ringing sound when struck; -- said of a
metal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mute swan</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a European
wild white swan (<spn>Cygnus olor</spn> syn. <spn>Cygnus gibbus</spn>),
which produces no loud notes, in distinction from the <contr>Trumpeter
swan</contr>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<usage>
<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Silent; dumb; speechless.</syn> --
<er>Mute</er>, <er>Silent</er>, <er>Dumb</er>. One is
<xex>silent</xex> who <xex>does</xex> not speak; one is <xex>dumb</xex>
who <xex>can</xex> not, for want of the proper organs; <as>as, a
<ex>dumb</ex> beast, etc.</as>; and hence, figuratively, we speak of a
person as struck <xex>dumb</xex> with astonishment, etc. One is
<xex>mute</xex> who is <xex>held back</xex> from speaking by some
special cause; <as>as, he was <ex>mute</ex> through fear; <ex>mute</ex>
astonishment, etc.</as> Such is the case with most of those who never
speak from childhood; they are not ordinarily <xex>dumb</xex>, but
<xex>mute</xex> because they are deaf, and therefore never learn to
talk; and hence their more appropriate name is
<xex>deaf-mutes</xex>.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They spake not a word;⟦br⟧
But, like <qex>dumb</qex> statues, or breathing stones,⟦br⟧
Gazed each on other.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All sat <qex>mute</qex>,⟦br⟧
Pondering the danger with deep thoughts.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>
⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>
</usage>

<p><ent>Mute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mute
<hw>Mute</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who does not speak,
whether from physical inability, unwillingness, or other cause.</def>
<specif>Specifically:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>One who, from deafness,
either congenital or from early life, is unable to use articulate
language; a deaf-mute.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A person employed by
undertakers at a funeral.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>A person whose part in
a play does not require him to speak.</def> <sd>(d)</sd> <def>Among the
Turks, an officer or attendant who is selected for his place because he
can not speak.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>A letter which represents no
sound; a silent letter; also, a close articulation; an element of speech
formed by a position of the mouth organs which stops the passage of the
breath; <as>as, <stype>p</stype>, <stype>b</stype>, <stype>d</stype>,
<stype>k</stype>, <stype>t</stype></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A little utensil made of brass,
ivory, or other material, so formed that it can be fixed in an erect
position on the bridge of a violin, or similar instrument, in order to
deaden or soften the tone.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>muted</ent>⟦br⟧
